Session 6. Tidyr, Dplyr

Parandzem Sargsyan, AUA, Metric

psargsyan@aua.am

October 5, 2019

Supplementary reading material: R for Data Science, Hadley Wickham & Garrett Grolemund

Introduction

Before doing data analysis, the data should go through data preparation process to make the data easier to work with. That process can contain several stages, one of which is data tidying.



First, tidyverse package should be installed. This package is designed to make it easy to install and load multiple ‘tidyverse’ packages in a single step (e.g.tidyr, dbplyr,ggplot2,etc). To see more run packageDescription("tidyverse").

#install.packages("tidyverse",dependencies = TRUE)
library(tidyverse)

tidyr

tidyr package provides a bunch of tools to help tidy up messy datasets.

The basic functions in tidyr that will help process, clean and manipulate data are the following ones which we will learn during this session:

  • spread()
  • gather()
  • separate()
  • unite()

Let’s take a look on 3 tables from tidyr package which represent the same data in different ways. view() can be used to see the data in a spreadsheet style in RStudio.

tidyr:: table1
tidyr:: table2
tidyr:: table3

From the above 3 tables, the tidy data will be the one which is much easier to work with. So, to make a dataset tidy there are three interrelated rules:

  1. Each variable must have its own column.
  2. Each observation must have its own row.
  3. Each value must have its own cell.

Spread()

This function is used when an observation is spread out across multiple rows.

The table 2 above shows that for the same country and same year (e.g. Afghanistan 1999), there are two rows. Instead there should have been only one. Let’s bring the second table to the format of the first one by using spread() function.

#1st option of the writing the code is with %>% operator
table2 %>%
  spread(key = type, 
         value = count)

The same code above can be written also using %>% operator.

spread(table2,
       key = type,
       value=count)

In the next codes, %>% operator will be used to call functions from the tidyr and dplyr packages just for the convinience. *To learn more about %>% operator go https://www.datacamp.com/community/tutorials/pipe-r-tutorial.*

gather()

This function is used to bring common attributes of data together as one variable. Table4a below shows that “year” instead of being single variable apears as a heading of two separate columns.

table4a

So, let’s use gather() to bring Table4a into more structured format, i.e. create new column for “year” variable.

tb4a<-table4a %>%
  gather(`1999`,`2000`,
         key = "year",
         value = "cases")
tb4a

Class Exercise: Bring table4b into more structured format and join to table4a.

Solution

tb4b<-table4b %>%
  gather(`1999`,`2000`,key = "year",value = "population")
tb4b

Let’s join table4a and table4b to bring the tables in the format of table1.

left_join(tb4a,tb4b, by=c("country","year"))

separate()

This function splits a variable into two variables by splitting wherever a separator character appears. Table 3 below shows that “cases” and “population” appear as single variable and values are separated only by “/”.

table3

So let’s use separate() funtion to create two separate variables for cases and population as it is in Table1.

table3 %>%
  separate(rate, #the column, which should be separated
           into = c("cases","population"), #new column names
           sep="/" #indicates by which character to separate
)

From the new Table3 above, we see that types of cases and population variables are of character type instead of being integer. So let’s change the code above a little bit by setting right types of variables.

table3 %>%
  separate(rate, #the column which should be separated
           into = c("cases","population"),  #new column names
           sep = "/", #separate by what
           convert = TRUE  #changing data type
)

Class Exercise: Separate year in table3 into two columns: 1st two digits-“century”, last tow digits-“year”.

Solution

table3 %>%
  separate(year, 
           into = c("century","year"),
           sep = 2, #defines how 
           convert = TRUE
)

Unite()

This function is the inverse of separate, i.e. it is used to merge two separate variables into one.

Let’s use Table 5 as an example.

table5

Let’s combine century and year.

table5 %>%
  unite(new, #name of new column
        century, year #columns which should be combined
)

Note: Automatically underscore (“_“) is created between combined values. Let’s modify the code above by putting”" which indicates that we don’t want any separator.

table5 %>%
  unite(new, #name of new column
        century, year, #columns which should be combined
        sep="",
        remove = TRUE #removes  input columns
)

dplyr

The basic functions in dplyr that will help transform the data (e.g. create new variables, renale variables, or summarise) are the following ones which we will learn during this session:

  • filter()
  • arrange()
  • select()
  • mutate()
  • summarize()
  • group_by()
#flights data will be used in the analysis
library(nycflights13)
#let's see how the data looks like
data_flight<-nycflights13::flights
head(data_flight)
str(data_flight)

filter()

Picking observations by their values.

Operators for value picking: >, >=, <, <=, != (not equal), and == (equal).

Let’s filter the data only for flights taken place in May.

data_flight %>%
  filter(month==5)

Let’s filter flights with more than 12 hour and destination was LAX.

data_flight %>%
  filter(hour>12,dest=="LAX") #multiple imput means "AND", i.e. both expressions must be true.

Other logical operators to use in the filter():

  • & is “and”,
  • | is “or”,
  • ! is “not”

Let’s filter for flights that taken place either on May OR June:

data_flight %>%
  filter(month==5 | month==6)
data_flight %>%
  filter(month %in% c(5,6))

filtering for missing data:

data_flight %>%
  filter(is.na(dep_delay) & is.na(arr_time))

arrange()

Reordering the rows.

data_flight %>%
  arrange(year, day, month)

Use desc() to re-order by a column in descending order:

data_flight %>%
  arrange(desc(month))

select()

From the data, picking only several variables by their names.

data_flight %>%
  select(month,day,dep_time, arr_time)
# Select all columns between year and day (inclusive)
data_flight %>%
  select(year:day)
# Select all columns except year and day
data_flight %>%
  select(-(year:day))

Some useful function to help to filter:

  • starts_with("abc"): matches names that begin with “abc”.
  • ends_with("xyz"): matches names that end with “xyz”.
  • contains("ijk"): matches names that contain “ijk”.
data_flight %>%
  select(starts_with("dep"))
data_flight %>%
  select(contains("sch"))

mutate()

Creating new variables with functions of existing variables. The main arithmetic operators can be used to create new variables: +, -, *, /, ^.

data_flight %>%
  mutate(difference=dep_delay - arr_delay)

let’s bring a new variable to the beginning.

data_flight %>%
  mutate(difference=dep_delay - arr_delay) %>%
  select(difference,everything())

If you only want to keep the new variables, use transmute():

data_flight %>%
  transmute(difference=dep_delay - arr_delay)

summarize(),group_by()

summarize: Collapsing many values down to a single summary.

group_by: this function changes the scope of each function from operating on the entire dataset to operating on it group-by-group.

data_flight %>%
  summarise(delay = mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE))
data_flight %>%
  summarise(median(hour, na.rm = TRUE))

Let’s calculate average delay for each month.

data_flight %>%
  group_by(month) %>% #first we need to group data by month
  summarise(delay=mean(dep_delay, na.rm = TRUE)) #then for each month calculate mean delay

Class exercise:

  1. group by destination
  2. calculate how many flights each destination has
  3. calculate average delay
  4. calculate average distance
  5. visualise relationship between delay and distance

Solution

sum_data<-data_flight %>%
  group_by(dest) %>%
  summarise(
    avg_delay=mean(arr_delay+dep_delay,na.rm = TRUE),
    avg_distance=mean(distance,na.rm = TRUE),
    num_flights=n()
  )
sum_data
ggplot(sum_data)+
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = avg_distance, y=avg_delay, size=num_flights),alpha=1/3)+
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = avg_distance, y=avg_delay),se = FALSE)

The graph above shows that delays increase when distance is up to 700-800miles, after which the delay starts decreasing.
